<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>DDB0085</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The Law Society of Scotland – Written evidence</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><br /><span style="color:#002f5f; font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Introduction</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The Law Society of Scotland aims to lead and support a successful and respected Scottish legal profession. Not only do we act in the interests of our solicitor members but we also have a clear responsibility to work in the public interest. That is why we actively engage and seek to assist in the legislative and public policy decision making processes. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 70.9pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">This response has been prepared on behalf of the Society by members of our Banking, Company and Insolvency Law sub-committee. This committee is comprised of senior and specialist lawyers (both in-house and private practice) and legal academics. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#002f5f; font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">General Comments</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#002f5f; font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The Society commends the principles behind the draft Deregulation Bill, namely to reduce bureaucracy, and is in general supportive of the Bill. However, we have a number of concerns about how the Bill proposes to implement its policy objective. Our specific comments are outlined below.</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#002f5f; font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Specific Comments</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#002f5f; font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#002f5f; font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Legislation no longer of practical use (Clauses 51 – 57) </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Clause 51 his allows a Minister of the Crown to make an order for legislation to cease to apply if the Minister considers it is of no practical use.</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> The Order can repeal or revoke the legislation or amend it.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">In terms of Clause 52, before making an Order under Section 51 which contains provisions which would be within the legislative competence of the Scottish Parliament, if it were contained in an Act of that Parliament, the Minister must obtain the consent of the Scottish Ministers. Clauses 52(2) and (3) apply a similar provision to Wales and Northern Ireland.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The Society questions whether it is appropriate for a Minister acting under Section 5, where the Order would contain a provision which would be within the legislative competence of the Scottish Parliament, that the Minister should only require the consent of Scottish Ministers and not the Scottish Parliament.</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> The lack of Parliamentary engagement in connection with such Orders which affects Scottish legislation or indeed Welsh or Northern Irish devolved legislation lacks proper democratic engagement.</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> These concerns also extend to Clause 57.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The provisions of Clauses 53, 54, 55 and 56 seem appropriate in terms of Parliamentary procedure.</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> The Society particularly approves of Clause 54 which relates to the procedure for consultation.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#002f5f; font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#002f5f; font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#002f5f; font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Auditors ceasing to hold office</span><span style="color:#002f5f; font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> (</span><span style="color:#002f5f; font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Schedule 4</span><span style="color:#002f5f; font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The Society is concerned about proposals to remove the requirement on listed and non-listed companies to notify the Registrar of Companies within 14 days when auditors resign.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Many members of the Law Society’s Banking, Company and Insolvency law sub-committee act for or have acted for individuals and large investing institutions registered in Scotland, whose investment decisions can frequently be significantly influenced by the financial and other information available publicly on underlying investee, or potential investee, companies.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Experience suggests that instability in auditors’ holding office is a significant negative factor influencing investors and potential investors (institutional and individual). Resignation of </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">auditors</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> mid-term can be the first clear indication of possible underlying financial difficulties or irregularities, or disconnects with management.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The Registry at Companies House is an early port of call for due diligence on all types of companies for making or withdrawing from investments. In an investment sector where significant amounts of investors’ money are moved by managers </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">daily,</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> and decisions are otherwise time critical, the earliest possible indication of events such as auditors’ unexpected resignation can be helpful and ultimately beneficial.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The Society therefore wishes to express its concerns on this point, which is considered potentially unhelpful to investing business entities and individuals, whilst approbating the remainder of the simplified notification provisions.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#002f5f; font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The authorisation of Insolvency Practitioners (Schedule 5, Part 6)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The Society is concerned about the concept of partial authorisation of Insolvency Practitioners. In England, bankruptcy and corporate insolvency legislation is separate, but in Scotland significant parts of corporate insolvency is linked to bankruptcy legislation. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The Insolvency (Scotland) Rules in their present form require reference to Scottish Bankruptcy law when an Insolvency Practitioner is appointed</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">as receiver, liquidator, </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">administrator</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> or CVA supervisor.  In contrast to the position in English law, the insolvency of a Scottish partnership is governed by Bankruptcy law, not corporate insolvency law and rules.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The Society would therefore question whether anyone could be an effective corporate Insolvency Practitioner in Scotland if they possessed little or no knowledge of bankruptcy legislation.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">September 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>